cs.IR, cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.LG, cs.CC 

This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with ranking functions for directed graphs, specifically PageRank. It also introduces graph-theoretic notions of quality for ranking functions, which is a common topic in IR. 

It could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category as it discusses the random walk algorithm used in PageRank and proposes improvements to it. 

The Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category is also a possibility as PageRank is commonly used in network analysis and the paper deals with improving its effectiveness in this context. 

The Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category is a possibility as PageRank can be seen as a form of unsupervised learning and the paper proposes improvements to its performance. 

Finally, the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category is a possibility as the paper discusses the complexity of computing PageRank and proposes improvements to its efficiency.
